#-    The soothing sound of raindrops meeting the roof, the vaporous flow of steam from the kettle, and the secure feeling the fireplace provided suddenly vanquished after the first detonation. The children whimpered following the blast, their wool cloaks no
#- longer comforting them. Parents tried to hush their young to little success. Sobs and the fading of the explosion hung in the air, and then silence.
   Another detonation, this time louder, closer. More whimpering from the children, soon silenced by
#- caring hands clenched over their mouths.
   Citizens anticipated their arrival, but not this soon. Not on such a peaceful day as this one. Hours before townspeople lined the canal, socializing and watching the steady flow of water under the blanket of
#- gray clouds. Rain soon engulfed the city, and the people migrated inside.
   But not the guardsmen. Sworn to protect the city, they remained outside the gates. Relations with a nearby city had grown tense after the canal was directed away.
#- Their crops had died, their people starved. As a last attempt to save their own people, and seek revenge, they marched to the gates with the finest armor and weaponry.
   Not soon after, messengers rushed from door to door, alerting the citizens of the
#- invasion. The townspeople bolted their doors shut and huddled with their families, awaiting what was to come.
   Another explosion. Even louder, even closer. What were they doing? Blasting their way through the layered walls? Leveling the homes and
#- businesses that lined the canal?
   Unaware, the family trembled in the now cold room. The only sound was the that of their breath, and the ringing in their ears that accompanied the dead silence.
   A few minutes elapsed from the last explosion. They
#- grew weary, holding their breath and then releasing it. Were they done? Or are they approaching?
   Beyond the window, a figure appeared. He stopped at the side of the canal, his back to the disquieted family. Male, cloaked, heavily armored.
#- The sword at his side, covered in thick, fresh blood, glowed. He gazed across the canal, scanning the endless facades of homes.
   No longer crying, the children dug their faces into the surcoats of their providers. They prayed the figure not turn his
#- visage towards their window.
   But he did. He looked through the glass, and into the eyes of the townspeople. He stood, watching them. No movement, no sound.
   Then, another earthshattering explosion. The house shook and the children screamed. 
#- 
